column39:
Hey out there! Welcome to this (sad excuse) for a profile page. I have no clue what you're even doing on this page because stalking people on CMS is just sad. (Hint: Stalking on Facebook is faaar more efficient than out here.). I assume you came here after seeing my name listed under the heading of "online users" - before you try messaging me here (yes, CMS has a messaging feature) calling me a ghot, do keep in mind:

(a) I'm probably not here online. CMS is just open on one of my browser tabs - always.
(b) While I do not agree with your accusation of being a ghot, there's nothing fundamentally wrong in being one. (Read the article "Ghot and Proud" in this magazine. And no, I didn't write that article.)

In case you're actually here to find out more about me (unlikely), my intro:

"My name is Rohit Dwivedula and my ID number is 2017A7PS0029H. I'm in CS. I'm from Rajahmundry, which is in Andhra Pradesh, and my hobbies include reading sci-fi, writing occasionally and debating."

Pretty generic. I agree. (Oh, and yeah - I have a habit of overusing the word 'generic'). Last year, when I first came to campus, saying that intro out loud was hard. I had to die a bit inside every time I made myself say that intro. I didn't have any fancy hobbies (skydiving, 'comparative Indian Mythology', etc). I don't dance, sing, perform, do stand-up or play a musical instrument. Never played a sport good enough to make it to the team. 'What did I do in life?' became a constant refrain at the back of my head. “Reading books” was too generic to sound serious. And debating - never really attended tournaments. Most of my debating experience was in the cocoon of my school, and I wasn’t sure if that even ‘counted’.

Am I just like one of those lifeless robots in the sci-fi books I read? Did I ever really have fun in my life? Others could pass off watching anime, TV series and movies as a hobby - I didn't do any of that either. I don't play a lot of video games (unless AOE counts :p). I still remember being asked what I do other than studying in one of my interactions with seniors (having ultra-thick glasses just promotes the idea). I had no answer. I spent that night thinking about the ‘sad’ existence I led.

With time, I realised most of it is in my own head. Most people don’t have fancy hobbies. Most people spend their days doing nothing earth-shattering. ‘Reading’ and ‘debating’ are perfectly legit things to do in your free time. I tried improving my non-existent design skill. I joined a bunch of departments and left them later. I joined a few clubs and made a small circle of friends. While this is probably sounding like a cliched story of how I built myself up and all, it’s not. The only thing that’s changed between last year and now is what’s inside my head. I no longer force myself to do things I’m 100% sure I would not enjoy. I do stuff I like, and ignore to a large extent stuff I don’t, despite how many others might like it. So, yeah. If you feel sad/unhappy/embarrassed that you have no hobbies. Don’t. Try something new, or keep doing what you like.

PS: Message me on Facebook/email if you want to talk. Peace. :)

PS2: (like a year later) I just realized I was, at one point of time, sleep-deprived + jobless enough to actually type out all this profile on CMS. Since it's here, might as well let it stay.
